      "result": "\u003coutput\u003e\n{\n  \"rating\": 4,\n  \"summary\": \"Pruner is correctly scoped: Group A keys (`provider`/`providers`/`channels`) are stripped via explicit `config.pop(key, None)` and Group B keys (`gateway`/`dashboard`/`api_server`) including `gateway.auth` bearer are provably preserved. No secret logging, no caching, no in-place sharing concerns. One real warning: the import-time disjointness assertion is disabled under `python -O`/`PYTHONOPTIMIZE`, undermining its stated role as a safety gate.\",\n  \"findings\": [\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"warning\",\n      \"location\": \"src/clawrium/core/hosts.py:289-291\",\n      \"issue\": \"Module-level `assert not (_PRUNED_AGENT_CONFIG_KEYS \u0026 _PRESERVED_AGENT_CONFIG_KEYS)` is a documented safety gate against a future maintainer widening the prune set into Group B (which would silently wipe `config.gateway.auth` and `dashboard`/`api_server` on every load). Python strips `assert` statements when run under `-O` or with `PYTHONOPTIMIZE=1`. Nothing in this repo's packaging (`uv tool install`) currently sets that, but the guard is brittle — a downstream packager or operator running with `PYTHONOPTIMIZE=1` (common in some container images) would silently lose the invariant.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Replace the `assert` with an unconditional check that survives optimization: `if _PRUNED_AGENT_CONFIG_KEYS \u0026 _PRESERVED_AGENT_CONFIG_KEYS: raise RuntimeError('Group B keys must never appear in _PRUNED_AGENT_CONFIG_KEYS')`. Same one-line cost, but the invariant is enforced regardless of optimization level.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"src/clawrium/cli/status.py:175-178\",\n      \"issue\": \"This callsite reads `claw_record.get('config', {}).get('provider', {}).get('type')` for the fleet-status display column. After pruning, that path will always be empty, so the column will always render `-` for the provider type. This is the silent-fallback pattern the prompt's question #2 calls out: the pruner removes the data but a stale reader keeps returning a default rather than failing loudly. Not a security regression (no secret is exposed; the value was a non-secret type string), but the user experience drift hides a real change.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Migrate `cli/status.py` to read the provider name from canonical `claw_record['providers']` + `providers.json` (the same pattern `_build_provider_overlays_from_attachments` uses in `core/lifecycle.py:552`). Either fix in this PR or open a follow-up issue and note it in the iter-2 review summary so the regression isn't silent.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"src/clawrium/core/hosts.py:294-316\",\n      \"issue\": \"Stale-secret cleanup benefit (re: prompt Q2) is real but partial — the prune happens on every load, but the cleaned-up dict is only persisted when an unrelated write path (`add_host`/`remove_host`/`update_host`/`save_hosts`) actually fires. A `hosts.json` with a leaked `config.channels.discord.bot_token` left over from a pre-#794 install will continue to sit on disk with that token until the operator next mutates a host. The pruner short-circuits in-memory reads, but the on-disk credential lingers.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"If the goal includes evicting stale credentials from the on-disk file as a security improvement (not just shrinking it on the next natural save), add a one-shot opportunistic save in `load_hosts()` when the load actually changed the dict — guarded by file-lock acquisition and `_PRUNED_AGENT_CONFIG_KEYS` having been popped on at least one record. Otherwise document explicitly in CHANGELOG that operators wanting immediate eviction should run a `clawctl agent \u003cnoop-update\u003e` to force a rewrite.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"recommendations\": [\n    \"Replace `assert` at hosts.py:289 with an unconditional `if/raise` so the Group A ∩ Group B invariant survives `python -O` / `PYTHONOPTIMIZE`.\",\n    \"Audit other readers of `config.provider`/`config.channels` (status.py:176, doctor.py, tui/data.py) for silent-fallback display regressions and migrate them to canonical sources, or document the display change in CHANGELOG.\",\n    \"Confirm no debug/trace logging anywhere in the load path dumps the full host dict (verified clean for hosts.py itself; spot-check callers of `load_hosts()` in tui and gui).\",\n    \"Add a regression test that loads a fixture hosts.json containing both Group A noise and Group B real values (including a non-empty `config.gateway.auth`), then asserts Group A is gone and `config.gateway.auth` is preserved byte-for-byte.\"\n  ],\n  \"metadata\": {\n    \"files_reviewed\": 4,\n    \"domain\": \"security-review\"\n  }\n}\n\u003c/output\u003e",
