      "result": "\u003coutput\u003e\n{\n  \"rating\": 4,\n  \"summary\": \"Clean, well-scoped load-time migration. The frozenset disjoint-set assertion, in-place mutation, and guard ordering are all correct against the actual on-disk file. One important observation: the diff as pasted in the review request appears to be missing the trailing `(` on the assert line, but the file on disk has `assert not (...), (\\\\n    \\\"...\\\"\\\\n)` — valid Python — so this is a diff-rendering artifact, not a defect.\",\n  \"findings\": [\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"src/clawrium/core/hosts.py:289\",\n      \"issue\": \"Diff-as-pasted vs. file-on-disk mismatch. The diff in the review request shows `assert not (...),\\\\n    \\\"msg\\\"\\\\n)` with no opening `(` for the closing paren — that would be a SyntaxError. The actual file (line 289) reads `assert not (...) , (` then the string then `)` — a parenthesized message for line continuation, which is valid. Verified by reading the file directly. No code change needed; just flagging that anyone reviewing only the diff text could be misled.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Consider rewriting on one line (`assert not (A \u0026 B), \\\"...\\\"`) if length permits — eliminates the wrap that confused the diff renderer.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"src/clawrium/core/hosts.py:283-284\",\n      \"issue\": \"The disjoint-set invariant is enforced by an `assert` that disappears under `python -O`. For a structural guarantee about what the migration can and cannot touch, a runtime check that survives optimization (or, better, deriving one set from the other) would be more robust. The risk model in the comment — 'a future maintainer widening _PRUNED into Group B would silently wipe them' — is exactly the case `-O` would defeat.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Either replace with `if _PRUNED_AGENT_CONFIG_KEYS \u0026 _PRESERVED_AGENT_CONFIG_KEYS: raise RuntimeError(...)